My family booked this restaurant for Mother's day  Sunday May 12th.  Beware the website doesn't say on Sundays it is buffett only. It is $35 per person which to me was too high price for the limited amount of food choices.   Also, my.mother doesn't eat half the food on the Buffett . We looked at the menu before making reservations and she would have loved the Catfish or Fried Chicken neither were part of the buffett.  On the Buffett was the following; oxtails, yams, macaroni and cheese, Turkey wings, collard greens, string beans, rice pilaf,, salmon, green salad and potatoes salad with rolls.  For dessert peach cobbler and plain thin slices of cake.  Pros of the Buffett:  diabetics and people with high blood pressure would love it.  The food wasn't too salty or too sweet.  The food was good but I like just a little more seasoning.  The staff are very professional and the owner Londel only charged half for my mother's meal after having the cook make a couple pieces of fried chicken so she wouldn't be disappointed on Mother's day.  The customer service goes a long way in my book and they exceeded it.  The atmosphere was great, warm and cosy.  I will try Londel's again when I can order from the menu. So not on a Sunday.  I hope this review was helpful.  Melinda

We dined today at Londel's in Harlem, NYC. It was my first time but it won't be my last. The occasion was a repast to celebrate the life of a dear friend and Londel's was one of her favorite places. We were greeted at the door by Londel himself. The staff is delightful and accommodating, the service is professional and the food was excellent. They opened early just for us because Londel wanted to honor our mutual friend who he loved. It showed in everything that was done for us today. Can't wait to get back. Thank you Londel's for your kindness, your courtesy and your excellence.

Londel's Supper Club is a Harlem Institute with the Impeccably dressed Londel's Davis at it's helm. It was for many years the dining political seat in Harlem where Govenors, Mayors and State Senators lunched in Harlem along with business, civic and clergy. Sunday Brunch remains a standing date for many in the community. The potato salad is the best, l spoke to the chef about it's origin ( a combination of his grandmother from South Carolina and the German master chef he labored under.
Delicious Sunday brunch. White linen on the tables. Very classic Harlem.

I went there only because the Black Party for Book Expo America was there on May 30, 2013. It took us nearly an hour to get a basket of bread and at least 90 minutes to get our food, which was disgusting. I could not believe that the place had been there so long. The waffles were hard enough to knock out a windowpane, the chicken was overcooked and greasy, the spinach had no taste whatsoever, and even the soda tasted suspect. Our waitress was the rudest one that I have had since I can recall. She acted like she was doing us a favor and slammed the plates down on the table like we were at a hole-in-the-wall diner. She never came back to ask if everything was okay but, of course, her tip was added into the bill. One person in my party had to get up and get his own bottle of hot sauce after waiting on it forever. I am one of those people who will brag about good restaurants and bring them business. This is not one of them. My first and last time going there. No excuse for it.

Lost our favorite Harlem soul food restaurant last year so gave this one a try.  Service is good but the food is lacking and the pricing is suspect.  Upon taking our order the waiter asked our table of six if we wanted the appetizer sampler which sounded great.  Problem is the appetizer sampler is actually charged as each individual appetizer so it ends up costing about $50.00.  Sampler means sample not throw all the appetizers on to one tray and charge separately.  The fried chicken was overcooked and hard.  They claim all their foods are fresh but the potato salad obviously came out of a third party container.  It had very little taste and the potato consistency indicated it had been sitting around.  My daughter complained that her baked potato and the consistency and taste of cardboard.  My mother-in-law did enjoy her catfish so that was a saving grace.  I have lived in an around New York city for 25 years and this has to be one of the worst if not worst meal I've ever had."
